<worksheet margin="1in" bottom="1.25cm">
    <title>Math 330 Delta Functions for Real</title>

<page>

<introduction>
    <p>
        A key construction in the theory of PDEs is the <m>\delta</m>-function. Indeed, we used it to solve the Cauchy problem for the heat equation and will use it in proving the Fourier Inversion Theorem. The key property is that 
<md>
(f\ast \delta)(x) = f(x),
</md>
where the convolution is defined as
<md>
    (f\ast g)(x) = \int_{0}^{\infty} f(x-y)g(y)\,dy. 
</md>
<em>Note:</em> We will need some assumptions about <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> to ensure the convolution converges (see theorem below). In order to really understand this fundamental property, we're just going to study the <m>\delta</m>-function for real.
    </p>
</introduction>

<definition>
    <statement>
        <p>
            A <term><m>\delta</m>-net</term> for a class of functions (e.g bounded and continuous on <m>\mathbb{R}</m>) is a parametrized family of functions <m>\{g_{\alpha}\}</m> with <m>\alpha &gt;0</m> such that
<md>
\lim_{\alpha\to 0^+} (f\ast g_{\alpha})(x) = f(x)
</md>
whenever <m>f</m> is in the indicated family.
        </p>
    </statement>
</definition>

<p>
    The idea here is that <m>\delta(x) = \lim_{\alpha\to 0} g_{\alpha}(x)</m> whenever <m>g_{\alpha}</m> is a <m>\delta</m>-net. Our goal now is to show how we can build <m>\delta</m>-nets. To this end, suppose <m>g</m> is a non-negative function such that
<md>
\int_{-\infty}^{\infty} g(x)\,dx = 1.
</md>
From this, we consider the family given by <m>g_{\alpha}(x)  = \dfrac{1}{\alpha} g\left(\dfrac{x}{\alpha}\right)</m>, where <m>\alpha&gt;0</m>.
</p>





<exercise>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Show that <m>\int_{-\infty}^{\infty} g_{\alpha}(x)\,dx = 1</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
</exercise>

<p>
    We will now prove the following theorem in a series of exercises:
</p>

<theorem>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Suppose <m>f</m> is a continuous function on <m>\mathbb{R}</m> such that <m>|f(x)|\leq M</m> for all <m>x\in \mathbb{R}</m>. With <m>g_{\alpha}</m> as above,
<md>
\lim_{\alpha\to 0^+} (f\ast g_{\alpha})(x) = f(x).
</md>
        </p>
    </statement>
</theorem>

<p>
 We prove this by showing that for any <m>\epsilon &gt;0</m> and <m>x\in\mathbb{R}</m>, there exists an <m>A&gt;0</m> such that whenever <m>\alpha &lt; A</m>,  <m>|f(x) - (f\ast g_{\alpha})(x)| &lt;\epsilon</m>.   
</p>

<exercise>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Why does showing that prove the theorem?
        </p>
    </statement>
</exercise>


<exercise>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Show that
<md>
    <mrow> |f(x) - (f\ast g_{\alpha})(x)| = \amp \left| \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} (f(x) - f(x-y))g_{\alpha}(y)\, dy\right|</mrow>
    <mrow> \leq \amp \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} |f(x) - f(x-y)|g_{\alpha}(y)\, dy. </mrow>
</md>
</p>
    </statement>
</exercise>

</page>          

<page>

<exercise>
<statement>
    <p>
        Using the continuity of <m>f</m>, show that there exists a <m>\delta &gt; 0</m> such that 
<md>
\int_{-\delta}^{\delta} |f(x) - f(x-y)| g_{\alpha}(y)\,dy &lt; \frac{\epsilon}{2},
</md>
when <m>|y|&lt;\delta</m>.
    </p>
</statement>
</exercise>

<p>
    Using the constant <m>\delta</m> from the previous exercise, we now have 
<md>
    <mrow>\int_{-\infty}^{\infty} |f(x) - f(x-y)| g_{\alpha}(y)\,dy= \amp \int_{-\infty}^{-\delta} |f(x) - f(x-y)| g_{\alpha}(y)\,dy + \int_{-\delta}^{\delta} |f(x) - f(x-y)| g_{\alpha}(y)\,dy +</mrow>
    <mrow> \amp \int_{\delta}^{\infty} |f(x) - f(x-y)| g_{\alpha}(y)\,dy</mrow>
    <mrow> &lt; \amp \int_{-\infty}^{-\delta} |f(x) - f(x-y)| g_{\alpha}(y)\,dy + \frac{\epsilon}{2} + </mrow>
    <mrow> \amp \int_{\delta}^{\infty} |f(x) - f(x-y)| g_{\alpha}(y)\,dy</mrow>
</md>


Now we need to make the two "tail" integrals small by choosing <m>\alpha</m> correctly.
</p>


<exercise>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Argue that 
<md>
    <mrow> \int_{\delta}^{\infty} |f(x) - f(x-y)| g_{\alpha}(y)\, dy \leq \amp \frac{2M}{\alpha} \int_{\delta}^{\infty} g\left(\frac{y}{\alpha}\right)\,dy</mrow>
    <mrow> = \amp 2M \int_{\delta/\alpha}^{\infty} g(u)\,du. </mrow>
</md>
and
<md>
    <mrow>\int_{-\infty}^{-\delta} |f(x) - f(x-y)| g_{\alpha}(y)\, dy \leq  \amp \frac{2M}{\alpha} \int_{-\infty}^{-\delta} g\left(\frac{y}{\alpha}\right)\,dy</mrow>
    <mrow> =  \amp 2M \int_{-\infty}^{-\delta/\alpha} g(u)\,du.</mrow>
</md>
        </p>
    </statement>
</exercise>

<p>
    Now, because <m>\int_{-\infty}^{\infty} g(x) \,dx = 1</m>, there exists a <m>b&gt;0</m> such that 
\[
\int_{-\infty}^{-b} g(u)\,du + \int_{b}^{\infty} g(u)\,du = 1-\int_{-b}^{b} g(u)\,du < \frac{\epsilon}{4M}.
\]
</p>




</page>

 


</worksheet>
